   <indicator ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output Indicator</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Number of countries provided technical support to strengthen NCD responses and number of globally-relevant UNDP or UNDP/WHO knowledge products on NCDs produced and release.</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2020">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">Eight countries supported to develop national NCD investment cases. One joint UNDP/WHO knowledge product on NCDs (set of Sectoral Briefs)</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Develop at least six national investment cases on NCDs or mental health, strengthen the capacity of the network of health economists engaged on investment approaches and develop at least two new tools for strengthening NCD governance.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">NCD investment cases delivered in Thailand, Peru, Russian Federation.

Mental health cases launched in Philippines and Uzbekistan and initiated in Kenya, Zimbabwe and Uganda.

Economist training held for more than 100 health economists and UN staff.

NCD Legal Environment Assessment guidance and National NCD Strategies Toolkit drafted.

Air pollution cost-of-illness study initiated in Nigeria. 

Alcohol control investment case methodology developed as part of the SAFER initiative and pilot initiated in Uganda. 

Since 2016 WHO and UNDP have jointly developed 18 NCD investment cases that have been linked to 20 policy or legal changes in line with the WHO-recommended &#x2018;best buy&#x2019; interventions on NCD prevention and control. 

In countries, where it is possible to assess progress in implementation and for which data is available, the investment case findings suggest that the measures implemented by the project governments will: yield at least US$50 million in economic gains (discounted for inflation) thanks to averted healthcare costs and productivity losses; and save more than 4,000 lives by the end of 2022.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">At least four national NCD investment cases completed in collaboration with WHO, national governments and the UN Interagency Task Force on NCDs; at least one global knowledge product on NCDs published.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Six national NCD investment cases were launched in Armenia, Cambodia, Ethiopia, Kazakhstan, the Philippines and Zambia. UNDP/WHO joint publication of Noncommunicable Disease Prevention and Control: a Guidance Note for Investment Cases. 

Among the government actions that were enacted following recommendations from these NCD investment cases are the adoption of a comprehensive tobacco control law in Armenia; the inclusion of NCD action in Cambodia&#x2019;s national development plan; a restructuring and increase of tobacco taxes in Ethiopia; passage of a new law in the Philippines increasing taxes on alcohol and e-cigarettes; and the inclusion of NCDs in Zambia&#x2019;s national development plan.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">At least three countries supported to undertake NCD investment cases. Development of at least two new investment case methodologies. At least one joint UNDP/WHO knowledge products.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Uganda, Nigeria and Botswana supported to develop NCD investment cases. UNDP/WHO Position Paper on COVID-19 and NCDs published. UNDP/WHO Guidance on Development of Mental Health Investment Cases published. Mental health investment case methodology put into practice in Philippines, Uzbekistan and Uganda. Air pollution cost-of-illness methodology developed for both household and ambient air pollution.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
